          "body": "Verse 21 is the moral climax of the chapter and one of the most psychologically precise moments in the entire Old Testament. The brothers, under pressure, speak to one another — not knowing Joseph understands — and name their crime with startling specificity: 'we saw the distress of his soul when he pleaded with us, yet we would not listen.' They have carried a detailed memory for twenty years: not just the fact of what they did, but the quality of it — the boy's distress, his pleading, their refusal. Guilt preserves what time would otherwise erode. Reuben's follow-up in verse 22 adds the dimension of forewarning: 'Did I not tell you, \"Do not sin against the boy\"?' He had warned them; they had not listened; now the reckoning (*darash*) for Joseph's blood has arrived. The word *darash* means 'to require, to seek out, to demand an accounting' — it is the word of legal reckoning. Reuben does not yet know that the accounting is being administered by the very person on whose behalf it is due. The narrator notes with devastating precision: 'They did not know that Joseph understood, for there was an interpreter between them' (42:23). Joseph weeps privately (42:24) — the first of many recorded moments of Joseph's tears in these chapters. His tears are not weakness; they are the mark of a man who loves those who wronged him and is grieved that repentance must come so hard."
